{"title_page": "David Watson (general)", "text_new": "{{other people||David Watson (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= Sir David Watson\n|image=William Orpen Major-General Sir David Watson.jpg\n|caption= Major-General Sir David Watson (portrait by Irish war artist [[William Orpen]], 1917\u201318)\n|birth_date= 7 February 1869\n|death_date= {{death date and age|1922|2|19|1869|2|7}}\n|birth_place= [[Quebec City]], [[Quebec]]\n|death_place= [[Quebec City]], [[Quebec]]\n|nickname=\n|allegiance=\n|branch= [[Canadian Corps]]\n|serviceyears=\n|rank= [[Major General|Major-General]]\n|unit=\n|commands= [[2nd (Eastern Ontario Regiment) Battalion, CEF|2nd Battalion, CEF]]<br/>5th Brigade, [[2nd Canadian Division]]<br/>[[4th Canadian Division]]\n|battles= [[World War I]]:\n*[[Second Battle of Ypres]]\n*[[Battle of Vimy Ridge]]\n*[[Battle of Passchendaele]]\n*[[Battle of Amiens (1918)|Battle of Amiens]]\n*[[Second Battle of Arras#Somme|Second Battle of Arras]]\n*[[Battle of Cambrai (1918)|Battle of Cambrai]]\n|awards= [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]]<br/>[[Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n|relations=\n|laterwork=\n}}\n\n[[Major General|Major-General]] '''Sir David Watson''', {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|KCB|CMG}} (7 February 1869 \u2013 19 February 1922) was a [[Canadians|Canadian]] journalist, newspaper owner, and General.\n\nBorn in [[Quebec City]], [[Quebec]], the son of William Watson and Jane Grant, Watson was a journalist with the ''Quebec Morning Chronicle'' (later called just ''Quebec Chronicle''). He later became general manager of the paper and general manager of its publisher.\n\nHe started his military career as a private in the 8th Regiment, Royal Rifles. He was promoted to lieutenant and then to captain in 1903, major in 1910, and lieutenant-colonel in 1912. In 1914, he enlisted in the [[Canadian Expeditionary Force]] and was soon given command of the [[2nd (Eastern Ontario Regiment) Battalion, CEF|2nd Battalion, CEF]]. He was promoted to Brigadier-General in 1915 and took command of the 5th Brigade, [[2nd Canadian Division]]. He was promoted to Major-General and took command of the [[4th Canadian Division]] upon its creation in 1916. He led his various commands in most of the major Canadian battles of World War I including [[Second Battle of Ypres|Second Ypres]], [[Battle of the Somme|the Somme]], [[Battle of Vimy Ridge|Vimy Ridge]], [[Battle of Passchendaele|Passchendaele]], [[Battle of Amiens (1918)|Amiens]], [[Second Battle of Arras#Somme|Second Arras]], and [[Battle of Cambrai (1918)|Cambrai]].\n\nIn late 1917, he and [[Victor Odlum]] saved their commanding officer, [[Arthur Currie]], from a career-ending charge of embezzlement by lending Currie enough money so that he could repay a large sum he had borrowed from regimental funds before the war.<ref>{{cite book| last = Berton| first = Pierre| title = Vimy| publisher = McLelland and Stewart| year = 1986| location = Toronto| pages = [https://archive.org/details/vimy0000bert/page/104 104\u2013105]| isbn = 0-7710-1339-6| url-access = registration| url = https://archive.org/details/vimy0000bert/page/104}}</ref>\n\nAfter the war, he resumed his job at the ''Quebec Chronicle'' and became the majority owner. He was also chairman of the Quebec Harbour Commission. He died in 1922.\n\n==Honours==\n*[[Croix de guerre 1914-1918 (France)|Croix de guerre]]<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=31465|page=9226|date=21 July 1919}}</ref> \u2013 France\n*[[Croix de guerre (Belgium)|Croix de guerre]] \u2013 Belgium\n*[[Order of St Michael and St George|C.M.G.]], 1917.\n*[[Order of the Bath|C.B.]], 1916.\n*[[Order of the Bath|K.C.B.]],<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=30450|page=1|date=28 December 1917}}</ref> 1918.\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{DictCanbio|ID=8411}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Watson, David}}\n[[Category:1869 births]]\n[[Category:1922 deaths]]\n[[Category:Canadian generals]]\n[[Category:Canadian Expeditionary Force officers]]\n[[Category:Canadian Companions of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:Canadian Knights Commander of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:People from Quebec City]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Croix de guerre (Belgium)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Croix de Guerre 1914\u20131918 (France)]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people||David Watson (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= Sir David Watson\n|image=William Orpen Major-General Sir David Watson.jpg\n|caption= Major-General Sir David Watson (portrait by Irish war artist [[William Orpen]], 1917\u201318)\n|birth_date= 7 February 1869\n|death_date= {{death date and age|1922|2|19|1869|2|7}}\n|birth_place= [[Quebec City]], [[Quebec]]\n|death_place= [[Quebec City]], [[Quebec]]\n|nickname=\n|allegiance=\n|branch= [[Canadian Corps]]\n|serviceyears=\n|rank= [[Major General|Major-General]]\n|unit=\n|commands= [[2nd (Eastern Ontario Regiment) Battalion, CEF|2nd Battalion, CEF]]<br/>5th Brigade, [[2nd Canadian Division]]<br/>[[4th Canadian Division]]\n|battles= [[World War I]]:\n*[[Second Battle of Ypres]]\n*[[Battle of Vimy Ridge]]\n*[[Battle of Passchendaele]]\n*[[Battle of Amiens (1918)|Battle of Amiens]]\n*[[Second Battle of Arras#Somme|Second Battle of Arras]]\n*[[Battle of Cambrai (1918)|Battle of Cambrai]]\n|awards= [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]]<br/>[[Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n|relations=\n|laterwork=\n}}\n\n[[Major General|Major-General]] '''Sir David Watson''', {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|KCB|CMG}} (7 February 1869 \u2013 19 February 1922) was a [[Canadians|Canadian]] journalist, newspaper owner, and General.\n\nBorn in [[Quebec City]], [[Quebec]], the son of William Watson and Jane Grant, Watson was a journalist with the ''Quebec Morning Chronicle'' (later called just ''Quebec Chronicle''). He later became general manager of the paper and general manager of its publisher.\n\nHe started his military career as a private in the 8th Regiment, Royal Rifles. He was promoted to lieutenant and then to captain in 1903, major in 1910, and lieutenant-colonel in 1912. In 1914, he enlisted in the [[Canadian Expeditionary Force]] and was soon given command of the [[2nd (Eastern Ontario Regiment) Battalion, CEF|2nd Battalion, CEF]]. He was promoted to Brigadier-General in 1915 and took command of the 5th Brigade, [[2nd Canadian Division]]. He was promoted to Major-General and took command of the [[4th Canadian Division]] upon its creation in 1916. He led his various commands in most of the major Canadian battles of World War I including [[Second Battle of Ypres|Second Ypres]], [[Battle of the Somme|the Somme]], [[Battle of Vimy Ridge|Vimy Ridge]], [[Battle of Passchendaele|Passchendaele]], [[Battle of Amiens (1918)|Amiens]], [[Second Battle of Arras#Somme|Second Arras]], and [[Battle of Cambrai (1918)|Cambrai]].\n\nIn late 1917, he and [[Victor Odlum]] saved their commanding officer, [[Arthur Currie]], from a career-ending charge of embezzlement by lending Currie enough money so that he could repay a large sum he had borrowed from regimental funds before the war.<ref>{{cite book| last = Berton| first = Pierre| title = Vimy| publisher = McLelland and Stewart| year = 1986| location = Toronto| pages = [https://archive.org/details/vimy0000bert/page/104 104\u2013105]| isbn = 0-7710-1339-6| url-access = registration| url = https://archive.org/details/vimy0000bert/page/104}}</ref>\n\nAfter the war, he resumed his job at the ''Quebec Chronicle'' and became the majority owner. He was also chairman of the Quebec Harbour Commission. He died in 1922.\n\n==Honours==\n*[[Croix de guerre 1914-1918 (France)|Croix de guerre]]<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=31465|page=9226|date=21 July 1919}}</ref> \u2013 France\n*[[Croix de Guerre]] \u2013 Belgium\n*[[Order of St Michael and St George|C.M.G.]], 1917.\n*[[Order of the Bath|C.B.]], 1916.\n*[[Order of the Bath|K.C.B.]],<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=30450|page=1|date=28 December 1917}}</ref> 1918.\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{DictCanbio|ID=8411}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Watson, David}}\n[[Category:1869 births]]\n[[Category:1922 deaths]]\n[[Category:Canadian generals]]\n[[Category:Canadian Expeditionary Force officers]]\n[[Category:Canadian Companions of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:Canadian Knights Commander of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:People from Quebec City]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Croix de guerre (Belgium)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Croix de Guerre 1914\u20131918 (France)]]\n", "name_user": "Isaac Sanolnacov", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHonours:disambiguation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Watson_(general)"}
